<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<section>
  <title>Summary</title>

  <p>
    In this chapter we introduced the fundamental ideas of probability and probability distributions, 
    which form the foundation of statistical inference. We discussed what probability means, 
    the different interpretations of probability, and the basic rules that probabilities must satisfy. 
    We then explored some of the most widely used probability distributions and learned how to investigate 
    them using the <em>Show Model</em> dialog in R-Instat. Throughout the chapter, R-Instat provided a 
    graphical interface for exploring probability distributions while automatically generating the 
    corresponding R commands in the background. The main topics covered in this chapter are summarised 
    below:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Probability theory versus statistics (<xref ref="probstats"/>)
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Frequentist versus Bayesian views of probability (<xref ref="probmeaning"/>)
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Basic rules of probability (<xref ref="basicprobability"/>)
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Probability distributions, including the Binomial distribution (<xref ref="binomial"/>), 
          the Normal distribution (<xref ref="normal"/>), and other commonly used distributions such as 
          the <m>t</m>, Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions (<xref ref="otherdists"/>).
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Using the <em>Show Model</em> dialog in R-Instat to calculate probabilities, 
          quantiles and densities, and to investigate how changing distribution parameters affects the shape 
          of probability distributions.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  

  <p>
    This chapter provides only an introduction to probability theory. 
    Probability is a substantial branch of mathematics with many specialised distributions 
    and applications that extend far beyond the scope of this book. Although we have 
    focused on a small number of commonly used distributions, many others exist and are 
    available within R-Instat. Fortunately, for most practical data analyses, a sound 
    understanding of the Binomial, Normal, <m>t</m>, Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions 
    is sufficient, since these form the basis of many statistical methods introduced later 
    in this book.
  </p>

  <p>
    While some introductory statistics texts give only a brief treatment of probability, 
    understanding these ideas makes it much easier to interpret the statistical methods that follow. 
    For example, later chapters introduce procedures such as confidence intervals, hypothesis tests and 
    analysis of variance. These methods rely on the probability distributions introduced here. Having 
    explored these distributions graphically in R-Instat and observed how their parameters influence their 
    shapes, you are now better prepared to understand the statistical reasoning behind these methods 
    rather than simply applying them as computational procedures.
  </p>

  <p>
    As you continue through the book, you will encounter these distributions repeatedly. 
    For example, the <m>t</m> distribution introduced in this chapter forms the basis of 
    the <m>t</m>-test (<xref ref="ttest"/>), while the Chi-square and <m>F</m> distributions are 
    used in several other inferential methods. You are encouraged to revisit the <em>Show Model</em> 
    dialog whenever you encounter a new statistical procedure, as it provides a useful way of visualising 
    the underlying probability distribution and reinforcing the concepts introduced in this chapter.
  </p>

</section>